We recommended that Management:
ensure clear segregation of duties between the billing and collection functions, with corresponding formal designation orders;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that ORs issued in the Tigaon Primary Hospital (TPH), formerly the Infirmary, reflect the itemized medical services billed to the patient and ensure that only authorized, properly designated, and bonded employees are allowed to handle the infirmary’s collections;
direct the Municipal Treasurer to instruct the collectors to include the doctor’s fees (per patient) in the OR issuance, then include its corresponding amount for subsequent payment to the doctors along with their monthly honorarium for proper recording of income and expenses in the books;
ensure that billing statements be pre-numbered for control and monitoring purposes and copies thereof are properly filed in and attached to corresponding ORs in the Report of Collections and Remittance/Deposits;
require the TPH personnel to exert their best efforts in accounting for all the unpaid hospital bills and promissory notes, and submit a report to the Municipal Accountant for appropriate recording in the books to establish the outstanding unpaid hospital bills and ensure monitoring of settlements thereof;
direct the Chief of TPH to request and coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer the establishment of a concrete and updated internal guidelines in the execution of promissory notes in accordance with R.A. 9439 and together with the Municipal Treasurer adopt an effective control in recording and settlement of promissory notes;
consider the increase of manpower in TPH to a reasonable number in order to properly segregate duties and responsibilities and to provide adequate medical services effectively and efficiently to its constituents; and
conduct a comprehensive evaluation of the operations and financial system of the Tigaon Primary Hospital and institutionalize a clearly defined procedures and guidelines on the granting of medical health care assistance to qualified constituents to prevent further losses in its operations.

We recommended that Management:
strictly adhere to the provisions of the procurement law in resorting to any of the alternative modes of procurement by considering whether the conditions that would warrant its use are all complied with;
improve procurement planning to attain, efficiency and to ensure that the most advantageous price/terms is obtained by the government;
submit a copy of the duly approved Annual Procurement Plan; and
monitor compliance of the terms of the MOA entered into with a supplier for the procurement of medicines and medical supplies.

We recommended that Management:
direct the GSO to conduct actual count of supplies and materials as of the first and second semesters of the current year, prepare the RPCI thereof in accordance with the required form, and properly reconcile it with other GSO records, such as Requisition and Issuance Slip (RIS) and Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI), and the accounting records;
require the concerned responsible person/s the submission of liquidation reports to the accounting office and COA for revalidation of the medicines purchased and outrightly debited to Due to NGAs account during CY 2021;
direct the Municipal Accountant to prospectively course thru the Inventory asset account any inventoriable purchases charged to the Trust Fund and record expense only upon submission of liquidation report and other related reports, in compliance with Section 114 of the said Manual and as a manner of audit trail; and
ensure sufficient, neat and conducive space in the LGU’s warehouse to safekeep items for stockpiling, either by hastening disposal of the present properties therein and/or if urgent and absolutely necessary, a temporary storage again but with express request and amended MOA for clear segregation and exclusive occupancy of the storage to avoid commingling of stocks.  Otherwise, avoid overstocking and consider purchasing adequate stocks only as needed for these food items are highly perishable and prone to wastage.

We recommended that Management:
immediately designate thru an Executive Order a point person/s who would ensure complete and final documentations for the donation and approved Deployment Plan, among others, and would actively coordinate not only for the E-trike deployment, but also the post-deployment responsibilities;
formally notify and/or make representation, if possible, to the DOE within CY 2022 regarding the current status, major concerns in the donation papers and deployment process, together with the LGU’s justifications and proposed actions to be taken, in order to seek technical assistance and effective advice therefor to mend the donated E-trikes;
direct the Municipal Accountant to record the 40 E-trikes costing ₱21,328,988.92 as asset and liability on the basis of LGU’s acceptance of the Deed of Donation; and
do other necessary steps to achieve the purposes for which the E-trikes were requested by the LGU-Tigaon and donated by DOE, and to prevent revocation thereof.

We recommended that Management:
direct the GFPS to maximize the utilization of GAD funds and monitor implementation of GAD PPAs to ensure that no PPAs are left unimplemented at year-end;
formulate a well-planned, clear and understandable GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) and prepare the Accomplishment Report (GAD AR)thereof with more comprehensive or concrete indication of the effect of the implemented GAD PPAs and containing other appropriate and adequate information, as well as attach required relevant supporting documents;
implement a defined monitoring and evaluation system to properly assess the status and impact of GAD PPAs on gender mainstreaming; and
strictly adhere to the prescribed rules and regulations on the utilization of fund for COVID-19-related expenditures.

We recommended that Management:

require the concerned accountable officers to settle/liquidate their outstanding cash advances, otherwise, enforce withholding of salary, in accordance with Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002; 


exert extra effort to retrieve records of the unliquidated cash advances of ₱2.56 million under Due from Officers and Employees account in order to identify/establish the accountable officer from which to require the refund/settlement of unliquidated amount;

make the necessary adjustments/corrections in the CA monitoring reports and SL to reflect the correct balance of unliquidated CA for the period;

stop the grant of additional cash advances to personnel with unliquidated cash advances until such time previous cash advances are fully settled; and

monitor and establish controls to ensure timely liquidation of cash advances such as requiring complete documentary requirements not only upon liquidation, but even upon granting of the same to establish accountability.

We recommended that Management:

exert efforts to retrieve pertinent documents to establish the validity of the dormant receivables and the LGU’s right to settle/collect them;


formally confirm inter-agency balances and/or make representation with already identified Implementing Agencies (IAs), primarily the concerned Barangays and associations within the locality of Tigaon, then demand liquidation as well as refund of any unexpended balance; 

prepare and issue demand letters addressed to the identified individuals under Other Receivables account;

consider requesting for write-off of validated and proven uncollectible receivables, specially those with totally unidentified transactions, provided that COA Circular 2016-005 is complied with; and

prospectively secure adequate records and maintain monitoring reports to support every inter-agency transfer in order to prevent dormancy in the books.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Assessor to hasten the updating of Assessment Roll and submit the same promptly to the MTO to establish an accurate RPT and SET receivables; 

require the Municipal Treasurer to update the RPT Account Register of Individual Taxpayers to reflect the correct amount of RPT and SET Receivables basing on the updated Assessment Roll from the Municipal Assessor and submit them to the Municipal Accountant as reference for the setting up of RPT and SET receivables at the beginning of the year;

through the Municipal Accountant, reconcile records with the Municipal Treasurer and thereafter, effect the adjusting entries to provide correct balances in the ensuing Financial Statements; and

intensify revenue collection efforts by strictly enforcing existing tax laws and adopt the most efficient, effective and economic measures to improve the LGU’s collection system and revenue generation.

